    "creation_date" : 1519935847,
    "answer_id" : 49058116,
    "question_id" : 1429860,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>With Java 10, you could now use <a href=\"https://download.java.net/java/jdk10/docs/api/java/util/Set.html#copyOf(java.util.Collection)\" rel=\"noreferrer\"><code>Set#copyOf</code></a> to easily convert a <code>List&lt;E&gt;</code> to an unmodifiable <code>Set&lt;E&gt;</code>:</p>\n\n<p>Example:</p>\n\n<pre><code>var set = Set.copyOf(list);\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>Keep in mind that this is an unordered operation, and <code>null</code> elements are <strong>not</strong> permitted, as it will throw a <code>NullPointerException</code>.</p>\n\n<p>If you wish for it to be modifiable, then simply pass it into the constructor a <code>Set</code> implementation.</p>\n"
