    "last_activity_date" : 1581596705,
    "creation_date" : 1581596705,
    "answer_id" : 60207826,
    "question_id" : 1429860,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>Remember that, converting from List to Set will remove duplicates from collection because List supports duplicates but Set does not support duplicates in Java.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Direct Conversion :</strong> The most common and simple way to convert a List to a Set</p>\n\n<pre><code>// Creating a list of strings\nList&lt;String&gt; list = Arrays.asList(\"One\", \"Two\", \"Three\", \"Four\");\n\n// Converting a list to set\nSet&lt;String&gt; set = new HashSet&lt;&gt;(list);\n</code></pre>\n\n<p><strong>Apache Commons Collections :</strong> You may also use the Commons Collections API to convert a List to a Set :-</p>\n\n<pre><code>// Creating a list of strings\nList&lt;String&gt; list = Arrays.asList(\"One\", \"Two\", \"Three\", \"Four\");\n\n// Creating a set with the same number of members in the list \nSet&lt;String&gt; set = new HashSet&lt;&gt;(4);\n\n// Adds all of the elements in the list to the target set\nCollectionUtils.addAll(set, list);\n</code></pre>\n\n<p><strong>Using Stream :</strong> Another way is to convert given list to stream, then stream to set :-</p>\n\n<pre><code>// Creating a list of strings \nList&lt;String&gt; list = Arrays.asList(\"One\", \"Two\", \"Three\", \"Four\"); \n\n// Converting to set using stream \nSet&lt;String&gt; set = list.stream().collect(Collectors.toSet()); \n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
